******
[1] Canada: (Saskatchewan)
Date: Sat 27 Oct 2007
Source: The Canadian Press [edited]
<http://canadianpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5jNe7A4GE6hZ89VeIRhAWKpiO-n3w>


A total of 3 game operations are under quarantine in Saskatchewan because
of chronic wasting disease [CWD]. One is a white-tailed deer operation
north of Moose Jaw, while the other 2 are hunt operations in Prince Albert.
Chronic wasting disease is a fatal neurological disorder that causes brain
lesions in deer and elk. Dr Cornelius Kylie of the Canadian Food Inspection
Agency confirms that the animals at the quarantined facilities will be
destroyed.

The affliction is similar to mad cow disease in cattle, and infected
animals rapidly lose weight and act strangely before death. Although the
exact cause of the disease is unknown, the agency says it is associated
with the presence of an abnormal protein called a prion.

In Alberta, the government has conducted periodic culls to control the
disease in wild deer populations. There is no treatment or vaccine
currently available for the disease, and there is no scientific evidence to
suggest the disease affects humans.

--
communicated by:
Terry S Singeltary Sr
